(1140, 2, '2012-01-12 12:34:41', '2012-01-12 12:34:41', 'Motion sickness, sea sickness and air sickness are collectively called motion sickness. Typical symptoms include headache, drowsiness, paleness, cold sweats, nausea, vomiting and dry mouth. Transportation sickness can strike anyone but is more common in children than adults and frames together women more than men. Symptoms can continue for several hours after the journey has ended, and it is such. not uncommon for a boat ride to feel the ground under a rock for several hours after we have gone ashore.\n\nShuttle Sick triggered when our brains, including through the balance board, perceive our body movements conflicting with the information our survey gives us. Motion sickness often triggered when children under a road trip reader, thus prevented from following the surrounding landscape with eyes.\n\nTravel Advice - preventive against motion sickness\n\n* Try to look out the window so your eyes and your equilibrium body does not provide conflicting information to your brain\n* Do not read, draw or watch movies while you drive, sail or fly.\n* Take antihistamines. Be aware that antihistamines are effective against motion sickness is not the same as the antihistamines you accept allerigi. The antihistamines that works on motion sickness seems sedative. The sedative effect can be exploited if you want to sleep during the journey. Anti Histamine is available as tablets and mixture over the counter at pharmacies. Can be used by children as young as 1 year.\n* Skopolaminplastre, available on prescription from your doctor. The patch should be applied 5-6 hours before traveling. Suitable for children over 10 years. Scopolamine for many will be more effective in treating motion sickness than antihistamine. Effects may persist for some time after you take the patch off. Scopolamine patches recommended for the elderly because it may have an adverse effect on the heart.', 'Motion sickness', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '