(1095, 2, '2012-01-12 10:40:39', '2012-01-12 10:40:39', 'Exposure to sun can cause burns and heatstroke. The nearer the equator you are, the greater the risk. The sun is strongest at midday, and the effect is enhanced by water, snow and sand. Sunbeams may serve even in the shade, and can penetrate the thin, loosely woven or tight clothing.\r\n\r\nSmall children should not be exposed to direct sun, and should never be decidedly sunbathe. Use physical sunscreen, and wearing the smaller children nationwide, thin and loose clothing. Remember a hat.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - sunbathing:\r\n\r\n* Do not stay in direct sun for several hours straight.\r\n* Avoid the strong midday sun.\r\n* Apply sunscreen with a high SPF every 2-4 hours and after swimming.\r\n* As a rule of thumb, you should use at least a handful of sunscreen when you apply yourself. Otherwise, you risk using too little.\r\n* Protect especially the ears, nose, shoulders and lips.\r\n* Use sunglasses with UV protection and fits tightly to the face.\r\n* Protect your head with a hat, cap or similar.\r\n* Stay in sunshade.\r\n* Drink plenty of fluids.', 'Sun', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'sun', '', '', '2012-06-18 10:20:38', '2012-06-18 10:20:38', '', 413, 'http://dlvs-uk.konscript.net/?page_id=1095', 0, 'page', '', 0),
