(1436, 1, '2012-01-12 11:48:49', '2012-01-12 11:48:49', 'Do you have a known allergy, you should also associated with travel to avoid the things that trigger your allergies.\r\n\r\nAllergies can show themselves in several ways:\r\n\r\n* Hay fever with runny or stuffy nose, and eyes that itch and watery.\r\n* Urticaria which appears with itching, redness and warmth of the skin, possibly buds one or more locations on the body.\r\n* Asthma / breathing difficulties / shortness of breath, which can also be triggered by allergies.\r\n* Closure example. of hands, eyes, tongue, face, fingers / toes. Any feeling of tightness in the throat.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - allergy:\r\n\r\n* If you have any known allergies, please remember to bring your usual allergy medication.\r\n* Do you suffer from food allergies and eating at a restaurant, ask if there are things you can not tolerate the food. Bring possibly a picture of it with you can not tolerate, it can facilitate the language barrier.\r\n* It may be a good idea, also for others to bring non-prescription drugs such as. antihistamine tablets and antihistamine-containing eye drops.\r\n* Are you allergic form of asthma and you do not know this from earlier, you should seek local physician.\r\n* Raises your lip and tongue, or you feel tightness in the throat, you should seek immediate medical attention.\r\n* Have you previously experienced severe allergic reactions, consult your GP before departure for relief.', 'Allergy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1036-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 11:48:49', '2012-01-12 11:48:49', '', 1036, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1036-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1437, 1, '2012-01-12 12:12:04', '2012-01-12 12:12:04', 'Altitude sickness is seen staying in heights from approx. 2,000 meters and above. Symptoms of mild altitude sickness are headache, insomnia, nausea and general malaise. About 20% will experience mild symptoms of altitude sickness already staying in 2200-2500 meters, which is not uncommon for many ski resorts. By staying in the 3,000 meters, for example. Himalayas or the Andes, the risk of experiencing altitude sickness real. The risk of getting altitude sickness is very individual, and some tolerate altitude better than others.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - the prevention of altitude sickness\r\n\r\n* Slow ascent, starting from ca. 3,000 meters altitude. Especially, the height will stay the night in is important, and one can go further up during the day. You should use 2-3 days of acclimation before the ascent increases individually with 300 to 500 feet before re-acclimatise for 2-3 days.\r\n* Drink plenty of fluids.\r\n* Avoid coffee, regular tea and alcoholic drinks which acts a diuretic.\r\n* Keep cool.\r\n* Avoid intense physical activity the first day.\r\n* Easy headache can be relieved with painkillers.\r\n* Altitude sickness can to some extent be prevented by taking 1 tablet of Diamox 250 mg nightly from one day before ascent until two days after arrival at final height. Diamox should be prescribed by a doctor.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - altitude sickness\r\n\r\nDanger signals are\r\n\r\n* Nausea\r\n* General malaise\r\n* Slight dizziness\r\n* Difficulty in sleeping\r\n\r\nAt altitudes up to 3,000 meters, these symptoms can often be remedied by remaining standing for a few days before further ascent. Performs symptoms at altitudes above 3,000 meters, you should try 300 to 500 meters down and acclimatise for at least 2-3 days for the symptoms disappear before further ascent.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - severe altitude sickness\r\n\r\n* Strong persistent headache not relieved by ordinary painkillers.\r\n* Strong nausea and vomiting.\r\n* Annoying dizziness, or orderly balance and steering effort.\r\n* Visual disturbances.\r\n* Pressure in the chest and troubled breathing or shortness of breath.\r\n* Swelling, called edema, which is typically seen around the eyes and ankles and hands.\r\n* Seizures.\r\n\r\nThese symptoms are signs of serious altitude sickness, which is an acute and potentially life threatening condition that requires immediate transport to the lowest height and immediate medical help.', 'Altitude sickness ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1062-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:12:04', '2012-01-12 12:12:04', '', 1062, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1062-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1438, 1, '2012-01-12 12:35:32', '2012-01-12 12:35:32', 'Bites from animals, can cause inflammation in the wound, poisoning, and in rare cases lead to more serious infections that require hospitalization.\r\n\r\nEspecially dangerous is rabies (hydrophobia), which can occur following bites from dogs, cats, monkeys, bats and other animals. Rabies is a viral disease that attacks the brain and untreated leads to the death.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - Teeth:\r\n\r\n* Always make sure your tetanus vaccination is still covering before leaving.\r\n* Avoid animal contact and be particularly aware that children can not cuddle with strangers and unfamiliar animals - even baby animals.\r\n* All animal bites should be immediately washed with soap and water.\r\n*Any foreign material removed.\r\n* For deep animal bites should consult doctor for evaluation of bidets and possibly start on antibiotics and tetanus vaccine. When possible rabies see below.\r\n* If wound fluid is treated with soap for 10 minutes 2-3 times daily. When the wound is completely dry, the usual wash enough.\r\n* If signs of infection in the form of increasing pain, throbbing, redness and swelling, suppurative, lymphadenopathy, blood poisoning (red lines stretching from the wound towards the nearest lymph nodes for example. Armpit or groin) or fever, seek medical advice immediately .\r\n\r\nTravel advice - rabies:\r\n\r\n* Have you been bitten by a rabies-suspect animal, wash the wound with soap and water. Then seek medical help immediately for start of vaccination against rabies. Is it possible, captured the suspects in order to observe whether they develop symptoms over the next day.\r\n* Where the animal is dead, bring it to the study.\r\n* Vaccination against rabies prior to departure is a possibility.\r\n\r\nHoses and other giftdyr\r\n\r\nSnakes attack rarely humans unprovoked. Snakes bite when they feel threatened or are amazed.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - avoid snakebite:\r\n\r\n* Wear boots and long pants whenever you are out walking in areas where you may encounter snakes.\r\n* Move slowly and stomp into the ground when walking through tall grass and the like so that the hoses have the opportunity to disappear. Snakes can not hear, but picks up vibrations through the earth.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - by snakebite:\r\n\r\n* If you are bitten, you stay calm. In many cases there is injected venom.\r\n* Avoid making unnecessary movements. Lie still after the bite. Movement increases blood circulation, causing a bug. venom to spread more quickly to the rest of the body.\r\n* If the bite occurred on an arm or a leg, this is well restrained.\r\n* Tie a string or a cloth around the bite. Try not to suck or cut the poison out!\r\n* Become urgently transported to a doctor or a hospital. You should if possible be carried or run.\r\n* If the snake is killed, so take it, so the species can be determined. Dead snakes transported over a stick or in a bag. Never touch an apparently dead snake.', 'Bite', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1047-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:35:32', '2012-01-12 12:35:32', '', 1047, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1047-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1439, 1, '2012-01-12 12:08:32', '2012-01-12 12:08:32', 'Colds caused by infection with flu virus and is not uncommon for travel. There are over 200 different viruses can cause colds. Colds typically contagious from the day before the disease breaks out for 1-3 days after disease outbreak. You typically infected through airborne droplets generated by coughing, sneezing, saliva or if, for example. via a handle, it has acquired infection on your hands, and then leads a hand up to eyes or nose.\r\n\r\nGenerally, the risk of colds 4 times as great in winter as in summer. There may be several reasons for colds in connection with travel.\r\n\r\nFor flights you will find yourself often for many hours with several hundred people in very little space. The more co-passengers there are and the longer the journey the greater the risk of becoming infected.\r\n\r\nMany indicate that air conditioning provides a cold, it is not clear whether this is the case. However, we know that air conditioning dries out the nasal membranes. Dry membranes are more vulnerable to infections. Moreover multiply cold virus better if you have cold air in the nose.\r\n\r\nWhen traveling to foreign places, there is also a greater risk that you are exposed to cold viruses as you have less resistance to the virus than you are exposed to at home.\r\n\r\nOutbreaks of cold sores caused by herpes simplex virus and it can be annoying when traveling.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - the prevention of colds:\r\n\r\n* It can be difficult to prevent colds, as the disease is transmitted from the day before you become ill, but the team as far as possible away to people who appear cold.\r\n* Wash hands frequently and avoid bringing them up to the face.\r\n* Ensure good ventilation if possible.\r\n* If one of your fellow travelers will be cold, it is important that he / she is instructed in good hand hygiene.\r\n* Turn down the air conditioning at night.\r\n* Slept like with decent cover in the form of blanket or similar.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - the relief of colds:\r\n\r\n* Nasal congestion can be alleviated by the use of nose drops or spray, available over the counter.\r\n* Pain in the neck can be relieved with lozenges ..\r\n* Many people find it soothing to hold your head over a basin with hot water and inhale the steam.\r\n* Sleeping with head elevated at night. For colds in children, you may want to lift the headboard of the bed, or use multiple pillows.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - colds and antibiotics:\r\n\r\n* Colds caused by viruses, and antibiotics such as penicillin has no effect on the disease. Only in case of complications, for example. in the form of sinusitis or otitis media, you should seek medical advice in order to evaluate whether there should be given antibiotics.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - cold sores:\r\n\r\n* By protecting your lips from sun and wind with a lip balm with sunscreen reduces the risk of getting cold sores.\r\n* Do you get a cold sore should wounded protected with lip balm with SPF.\r\n* At the first signs of outbreak (swollen and tingling around the lips area), started treatment with ointment against herpes virus', 'Colds', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1056-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:08:32', '2012-01-12 12:08:32', '', 1056, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1056-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1440, 1, '2012-01-12 11:57:35', '2012-01-12 11:57:35', 'There is a high risk of contracting diarrhea during travel abroad. The reason is that drinking water is often polluted, and that food is prepared / processed less hygienic than we are accustomed to. The diarrhea is often caused by infection with bacteria, viruses or worms / parasites, all of which can be killed by cooking. Another cause of transmission is that you are going to put his fingers in his mouth after you have washed hands in contaminated water or touched by, for example. soiled banknotes.\r\n\r\nCertain serious diseases such as cholera, typhoid and infectious hepatitis (hepatitis A), which is transmitted by contaminated food or drink that you can vaccinate against. The vaccine against cholera is also no coverage against ordinary tourist diarrhea.\r\nTravel advice - the prevention of diarrhea:\r\n\r\n* Eat only foods that are sufficiently cooked by boiling or by subscription immediately before consumption.\r\n* Do not drink tap water, only bottled water which you have opened.\r\n* Choose beverages that are cooked eg. coffee, tea or carbonated liquids in bottles with caps as beer and soda. Always make sure that it is you who opens your beverages. Use straws if possible.\r\n* Eat only fruit that can be peeled or peeled and do it yourself.\r\n* Avoid drinking tap water.\r\n* Avoid ice cubes.\r\n* Avoid eating all kinds of ice cream.\r\n* Avoid raw foods such as. lettuce, raw egg yolk and raw shellfish and fish.\r\n* You can prevent diarrhea by eating pills containing lactic acid bacteria (eg Idoform), which helps to protect the intestinal mucosa.\r\n* Consider vaccination against cholera and typhoid.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - the treatment of diarrhea:\r\n\r\n* Try to rest.\r\n* Eat plenty of fluids, especially water, sometimes. tea with little sugar or purchase rehydreringsvæske (available as powder is mixed in water) at the pharmacy.\r\n* Is the diarrhea bloody or you feel generally weakened by high fever, you should immediately seek medical help.\r\n* For diarrhea you can take antibiotics. 1 tablet ciprofloxacin 500 mg as single dose or tbl azithromycin 500 mg as single dose the first day and then tbl azithromycin 250 mg of DGL for up to 4 days. Preparation chosen destination. Ciprofloxacin and azithromycin are prescription drugs.\r\n* The medicine is taken as early as possible by nausea, abdominal pain or diarrhea begins.\r\n* Ciprofloxacin should not be used by children and pregnant women. Can be used by breastfeeding\r\n* For children and pregnant women are recommended azithromycin.\r\n* Stops medication, available over the counter may be used kortvarrigt in 1-2 days by adults, preferably in combination with antibiotics. Should not be used by children or bloody or mucoid diarrhea.', 'Diarrhea', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1044-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 11:57:35', '2012-01-12 11:57:35', '', 1044, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1044-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1441, 1, '2012-01-12 12:06:10', '2012-01-12 12:06:10', 'Fever can be caused by many things, and should always be compared with other symptoms, to find out what disease it is, and whether to seek medical or not. As a rule of thumb, you should see a doctor urgently if you feel generally weak or are unsure whether the fever can be caused by serious illness. Are you in areas with malaria, you should always consider seeking medical advice for fever.\r\n\r\nSmaller children''s temperature can rise quickly to 39 - 40 ° C even in light infections. Here it is important to observe the child''s general condition. Eating, drinking, peeing and playing child, you can wait and see, but the child will be dull, without appetite, and pale, you should immediately consult a doctor with the child. In those areas of the world where there is risk for malaria, you should always be extra vigilant, and as soon as possible find out whether malaria causes fever (blood test), regardless the child''s general condition.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - Fever:\r\n\r\n* Remember to bring a thermometer.\r\n* Drink plenty, preferably bottled water, sodas and non-alokoholiske drink. Remember that coffee and plain tea will have a slightly diuretic.\r\n* Remove most of clothes, so the body can lose heat.\r\n* Use a fan for cooling.\r\n* Add if necessary cold and wet cloth on the forehead, wrists and chest.\r\n* Consult a physician if the fever rises above 40 ° C.\r\n* Consult a physician if the fever does not decline within 1-2 days.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Fever', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1050-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:06:10', '2012-01-12 12:06:10', '', 1050, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1050-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1442, 1, '2012-01-12 12:17:17', '2012-01-12 12:17:17', 'All food is a potential source of infection. Be careful when choosing what you eat. This will reduce the risk of tourist diarrhea and more serious infections such as. infectious hepatitis, cholera, typhoid and dysentery.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - food:\r\n\r\n* Always keep a good hand hygiene.\r\n* Avoid putting fingers in their mouths.\r\n* Cook food itself if possible.\r\n* Stick to the safe food and stay away from the unsafe food:\r\n\r\nSAFE FOODS\r\n\r\n* Freshly boiled rice.\r\n* Freshly cooked pasta.\r\n* Scalding hot coffee and tea.\r\n* Bread.\r\n* Although tampering / peeled fruit.\r\n* Freshly boiled / nystegt food.\r\n* Bottled water.\r\n* Drinking from the bottle as you open\r\n\r\nUnsafe food\r\n\r\n* Ice cream and ice cubes.\r\n* Salads.\r\n* Uncooked vegetables.\r\n* Raw fish or raw meat.\r\n* Buffetmad\r\n* Unpasteurized milk products.\r\n* Water from the tap.\r\n* Fruits you have not tampered or garbage.\r\n* Dressing containing raw eggs such. mayonnaise.', 'Food', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1072-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:17:17', '2012-01-12 12:17:17', '', 1072, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1072-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
