(1445, 1, '2012-01-12 12:13:35', '2012-01-12 12:13:35', 'A wide range of diseases in the tropics transmitted by mosquitoes. Malaria is transmitted by a mosquito that is most active at night, whereas denque fever, yellow fever and Japanese encephalitis transmitted by mosquitoes are most active during the day.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - insect bites\r\n\r\n* Wear long pants, socks and sweaters with long sleeves.\r\n* Wear like clothes in bright colors. Dark colors attract mosquitoes.\r\n* Use an insect repellent agent on the skin. Sleeping under a mosquito net impregnated against mosquitoes, every night. Sleeping anywhere in rooms with mosquito nets mounted on the windows or in rooms with air conditioning.\r\n* If your bedroom does not have air conditioning or mosquito nets for windows, the room should be sprayed with an insecticide.\r\n* The connectors can insect pin or local anesthetic creams used against itching and pain.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - mosquito nets\r\n\r\n* Along with the regular use of preventive anti-malarial drugs are mosquito nets around the bed the most effective method for preventing malaria.\r\n* The effect of bed nets increased 2-4 times by impregnation with permetrin or deltametrin.\r\n* Mosquito nets impregnated with permetrin is illegal to import, sell or use in the EU. Environmental Protection Agency is just now processing an application for permission to sell bed nets impregnated with deltametrin.\r\n* Consistent use of mosquito nets around the bed reduces the risk of getting malaria by approx. 50%. An impregnated nets should be re-impregnated at 6 months.\r\n* The mosquito net must be so large that it can be bent in under the mattress or sleeping pad and must hang loose so that you can not inadvertently come into contact with it during the night.\r\n\r\n\r\nTravel advice - insect repellents\r\n\r\n* In Denmark sold products AUTANES and Mosi-guard. These products are considered equivalent to such. Jungle Oil containing DEET and not available in Denmark.\r\n* AUTANES, Mosi-guard and DEET can irritate the skin and can not come in contact with mucous membranes, for example. eyes, nose and mouth. AUTANES should not be used on children under 3 years.\r\n* American Health Care recommends the use of DEET-containing products to children as young as 2 months. So Jungle Oil bought abroad can be used for the little ones.', 'Insect bites', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1065-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:13:35', '2012-01-12 12:13:35', '', 1065, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1065-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1446, 1, '2012-01-12 12:28:01', '2012-01-12 12:28:01', 'The rules and coverage areas and travel insurance can vary from company to company. It is important to be properly covered, or you''ll risk being met with extraordinary large claims for payment of a received treatment abroad.\r\n\r\nThe Yellow Card provides coverage for illness in the short tourist trips within Europe. Health insurance card does not cover hjemtransport.Det is also important to examine coverage for lost holidays, canceled vacations, lost baggage and possible accidents. Be aware that certain sports (eg. Diving, skiing, climbing, paragliding) can be excluded coverage at all.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - travel insurance:\r\n\r\n* Always have an adequate travel insurance.\r\n* Check if your travel provider has a special arrangement with an insurance company.\r\n* Check if your regular insurance company has an annual travel insurance.\r\n\r\nThe Yellow Card\r\n\r\n* You are covered by your yellow health card in another country, you\r\n* Travels in less than a month.\r\n* Is on a holiday or study tour.\r\n* Travel within the EU and EEA as well as some small states.\r\n* Not have a chronic illness such as hypertension.\r\n\r\nRecovery of costs\r\n\r\n* The Yellow Card ensures that you receive reimbursement of your expenses, equal to the domestic coverage.\r\n* You may risk having to pay for medical care and medications directly at the resort.\r\n* Remember to get receipts for your expenses.\r\n* You can recover your expenses by contacting the SOS International. You should always file a claim form. You can report damage online at the SOS website.\r\n* If in doubt abroad you can use the phone number printed on the back of the card and get guidance from the telephone-call service, which is open around the clock.\r\n\r\nEU Blue card\r\n\r\nYou must have a European blue card on travel to an EU / EEA country when you:\r\n\r\n* Must be gone longer than 30 days.\r\n* Do an internship or an au pair.\r\n* Study or receive vocational training.\r\n* If you have a chronic illness.\r\n* If you must work your Danish employers abroad, you must have an approved E101 from the Social Security Agency, to get the Blue card.\r\n* The blue EU Health Insurance Card is free. You can order it from your municipality''s citizen service.', 'Insurance', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1089-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:28:01', '2012-01-12 12:28:01', '', 1089, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1089-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1447, 1, '2012-01-12 12:19:07', '2012-01-12 12:19:07', 'For malaria develops the infected seizures with fever, malaise and complications in the worst cases can be fatal. Malaria is caused by a tiny parasite that lives in blood. Malaria parasite transmitted by mosquito bites from malaria. Malaria mosquitoes are most active at night.\r\n\r\nMalaria is one of the major causes of morbidity and mortality worldwide. It is estimated that infects 300 million people per year, die ca. 1 million (mostly children under 5 years were infected in sub-Saharan Africa).\r\n\r\nEach year there are about 100 Danes who are infected with malaria while traveling. Among travelers who are treated for malaria after returning there will be 0.5-1% deaths. Most are infected in Africa.\r\n\r\nMalaria occurs in all continents except Europe. There are areas where the risk is greater than others. Therefore builds all the information about malaria prevention in individual counseling. This should take into account travel, distance traveled, the traveler''s age, sensitization and / or other diseases of the traveler.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - Malaria:\r\n\r\n* Take preventative malaria medication if you need an area where there is a real risk of malaria. Be accurate in taking the preventative medicine. Read and always follow the directions on the package (see section on malaria medication).\r\n* Use insect repellent agent (see section on insect bites).\r\n* Sleep under a mosquito net which is impregnated (see section on insect bites).\r\n* Fever during and up to 3 months stay in malarial areas can not be explained adequately by other means, be considered malaria until proven otherwise.\r\n\r\n\r\nPrevalence of malaria\r\n\r\nUsing the link below you can get an impression of the prevalence of malaria at your destination and get a recommendation of any need for preventive malaria medication\r\nhttp://cdc-malaria.ncsa.uiuc.edu/\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Malaria', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1075-revision-4',