(1448, 1, '2012-01-12 12:22:06', '2012-01-12 12:22:06', 'Preventive anti-malarial drugs, along with consistent use of mosquito nets over the bed at night the main means of preventing malaria. There is no way that is fully effective in preventing malaria and no malaria agent is free from side effects. It is therefore important that the choice of malaria means adapted to travel and journey length, so that the risk of malaria and the risk of adverse effects balanced against each other.\r\n\r\nSide effects and anti-malarial drugs\r\n\r\nAll medicines can have side effects. Side effects are usually mild and transient.\r\n\r\n* Preventative Malaria medication is well tolerated by most people.\r\n* Mild side effects from antimalarial drugs is seen quite frequently.\r\n* Side effects of malaria medication is tolerated well by most, but whatever preventive medicine as selected, 2-5% (equivalent to 1 out of 30) stop taking medication because of side effects.\r\n* Serious side effects are very rare.\r\n\r\nPills to prevent malaria\r\n\r\n* Ercoquin (chloroquine).\r\n* Lariam (mefloquine).\r\n* Vibradox (doxycycline).\r\n* Malarone (atavaquon + proguanil).\r\n* Paludrine (proguanil) - can only be bought in Denmark with special permission. Danish Medical Vaccination Service (DLVS) authorized to slicing Paludrine.\r\n\r\nAbout malaria medication\r\n\r\nErcoquin recommended as first choice in Denmark and by the WHO when traveling to malaria areas. There is, however, emerged resistant malaria parasites in several places in the world and Ercoquin recommended now only a few destinations, eg. in Central America.\r\n\r\nVibradox, Lariam and Malarone seen in Denmark and by the WHO as being equivalent medicine to prevent malaria in areas with Ercoquinresistens.\r\n\r\nBelow is a brief review of the preventative malaria medication. When side effects have focused on the most common. The brief review can not replace a thorough reading of the leaflet that comes with the purchase of medicine at the pharmacy. Malaria medicines are only available on prescription.\r\n\r\nErcoquin (chloroquine)\r\n\r\nEffective and affordable cure for malaria. Due to the development of resistance in malaria parasite can Ercoquin currently only used when traveling to a few countries typically in Central America. Can be used by children and pregnant women.\r\nUse: Once a week, from one week before and 4 weeks after exposure to the malaria area.\r\nSide effects: Fatigue is frequent side effect. Others include abdominal pain, nausea, bloated stomach, headaches, dizziness, rash and itching. By taking Ercoquin may occur blurred vision which becomes normal again 8-16 hours after ingestion. Therefore, it is a good idea to take the tablets for dinner.\r\nPrecautions: Do not be taken by patients with psoriasis, chloroquine allergy, myasthenia gravis, retinopathy, epilepsy or severe hearing loss. Should not be taken with digoxin.\r\nBreastfeeding: Can be used.\r\n\r\nMalarone (atavaquon + proguanil)\r\n\r\nMalarone can be used to prevent malaria Ercoquinresistent. Malarone is relatively expensive and costs approx. 25 dollars a day. Can be used by children. Not to be used by pregnant women.\r\nUsage: taken once daily from one day before and 7 days of stay in a malaria area.\r\nSide effects: Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain and diarrhea.\r\nPrecautions: Do not be taken by patients with severe renal impairment or patients with allergy to atavaquon or proguanil.\r\nBreastfeeding: Can not be used.\r\n\r\nVibradox (doxycycline)\r\n\r\nVibradox can be used to prevent malaria Ercoquinresistent. Vibradox is actually a antiobiotika against bacteria, but also has good activity against malaria. Doxycycline should not be used by children under 12 years old or pregnant.\r\nUsage: taken once daily from one day before and 4 weeks after exposure to the malaria area.\r\nSide effects: Nausea. Can increase sensitivity to sunlight, so there should be worn sunscreen and caution by staying in the sun.\r\nPrecautions: Do not be taken by allergy to doxycycline. Dose reduction of renal or liver failure.\r\nBreastfeeding: Can not be used.\r\n\r\nLariam (mefloquine)\r\n\r\nLariam can be used to prevent malaria in areas with Ercoquinresistens. Because of psychiatric side effects, including nightmares, recommends Danish doctors Vaccination Service (DLVS) only needed in rare cases, for example. by positive experiences with the use of Lariam previously. Should not be used by pregnant and pregnancy should be avoided for 3 months after use.\r\nUse: Do a weekly no later than one week before and 4 weeks after exposure to the malaria area. Should be taken with food to prevent vomiting.\r\nSide effects: Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhea, headache, drowsiness, dizziness and sleep disturbances among others nightmares. Of uncommon events, other psychiatric side effects include: hallucinations, psychosis, agitation, anxiety, depression, confusion and aggressiveness. The psychological side effects cease after use.\r\nPrecautions: Should not be used by persons with mental disorders, epilepsy or hepatic impairment. Not for use by mefloquine allergy. Because of the risk of psychiatric side effects allows some dive centers do not use Lariam. First Lariam is started you should start 4 weeks before departure, with most psychiatric side effects occurring within 3 weeks, so that you may have time to switch to another product.\r\nBreastfeeding: Should not be used.\r\n\r\nPaludrine (proguanil)\r\n\r\nPaludrine In combination with Ercoquin used in few countries. Paludrine not marketed in Denmark longer and are available only with special permission. For areas where before recommended Ercoquin and Paludrine in combination, you can now use Malarone, Lariam or Vibradox. Paludrine in combination with Ercoquin can be used for pregnant women, see below.\r\n\r\nMalaria and pregnancy\r\n\r\nDanish Medical Vaccination Service (DLVS) advises all pregnant women to travel to areas with malaria. Malaria in pregnancy carries an increased risk for both mother and child. Are you pregnant, you should only travel to areas with malaria, if absolutely necessary. Both Ercoquin and Paludrine can be used during pregnancy. If a pregnant consume Paludrine tablets, she should also take a tablet of 5 mg folic acid daily. DLVS have permission to print Paludrine in special cases, including for pregnant women.\r\n\r\nSelection of malaria medicine to your destination\r\n\r\nUsing the link below you can get an impression of the prevalence of malaria and what medicine can be used at your destination.\r\nhttp://cdc-malaria.ncsa.uiuc.edu/', 'Malaria medication ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1079-revision-5', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:22:06', '2012-01-12 12:22:06', '', 1079, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1079-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1449, 1, '2012-01-12 12:34:57', '2012-01-12 12:34:57', 'Motion sickness, sea sickness and air sickness are collectively called motion sickness. Typical symptoms include headache, drowsiness, paleness, cold sweats, nausea, vomiting and dry mouth. Transportation sickness can strike anyone but is more common in children than adults and frames together women more than men. Symptoms can continue for several hours after the journey has ended, and it is such. not uncommon for a boat ride to feel the ground under a rock for several hours after we have gone ashore.\r\n\r\nShuttle Sick triggered when our brains, including through the balance board, perceive our body movements conflicting with the information our survey gives us. Motion sickness often triggered when children under a road trip reader, thus prevented from following the surrounding landscape with eyes.\r\n\r\nTravel Advice - preventive against motion sickness\r\n\r\n* Try to look out the window so your eyes and your equilibrium body does not provide conflicting information to your brain\r\n* Do not read, draw or watch movies while you drive, sail or fly.\r\n* Take antihistamines. Be aware that antihistamines are effective against motion sickness is not the same as the antihistamines you accept allerigi. The antihistamines that works on motion sickness seems sedative. The sedative effect can be exploited if you want to sleep during the journey. Anti Histamine is available as tablets and mixture over the counter at pharmacies. Can be used by children as young as 1 year.\r\n* Skopolaminplastre, available on prescription from your doctor. The patch should be applied 5-6 hours before traveling. Suitable for children over 10 years. Scopolamine for many will be more effective in treating motion sickness than antihistamine. Effects may persist for some time after you take the patch off. Scopolamine patches recommended for the elderly because it may have an adverse effect on the heart.', 'Motion sickness', '', 'inherit',