(1450, 1, '2012-01-12 12:30:19', '2012-01-12 12:30:19', 'It is annoying to have to miss some experiences or not being able to enjoy them fully, because you have pain. It may be headache, pain from joints and muscles, too much sun or pain from the stings and bites.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - pain:\r\n\r\n* Bring your usual prescription medications for pain.\r\n* Consider bring analgesic cream or gel which is available over the counter. Custard lubricated or massaged on the painful rewarding area 3-4 times a day for sore muscles. Remember to wash your hands afterwards.\r\n* Ice pack may be used for swollen joints in 10 - 20 minutes repeated after 1 hour. Keep a cloth between the ice pack and skin to avoid frostbite.\r\n* There ice packs which no prior chilling. These can be bought in many sports stores.\r\n* Local anesthesia can be smeared sunburned skin or insect bites.', 'Pain', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1092-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:30:19', '2012-01-12 12:30:19', '', 1092, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1092-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1451, 1, '2012-01-12 12:15:27', '2012-01-12 12:15:27', 'Venereal diseases such as HIV, hepatitis B, gonorrhea, chlamydia and syphilis occur worldwide. The incidence is especially high among prostitutes. In some parts of the world, such as sub-Saharan Africa and Southeast Asia, the incidence of the deadly disease HIV and hepatitis B is very high.\r\n\r\nUsing a condom provides good protection against STDs, but the protection is not 100 percent. Although the journey is of longer duration and they fall in love with a new partner, use condoms until you are sure that the new partner is not carrying an STD.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - STDs:\r\n\r\n* Always use a condom.\r\n* Keep yourself to have condoms on the trip and check the expiration date.\r\n* Avoid having sex with prostitutes.', 'Sexually transmitted diseases', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1068-revision-5', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:15:27', '2012-01-12 12:15:27', '', 1068, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1068-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1452, 1, '2012-01-12 12:32:52', '2012-01-12 12:32:52', 'Have you been bitten, cut, fallen or have otherwise been unfortunate and sustained wounds, the wound washed with soap and water. Debris removal. Remember that water must be clean.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - wounds and blisters:\r\n\r\n* Always make sure your tetanus vaccination is still covering before leaving.\r\n* Clean the wound thoroughly with soap and water.\r\n* Remove any objects.\r\n* Make sure the wound is kept clean.\r\n* Use clean dressings and change dressings daily.\r\n* Protect blisters with specially vabelplaster.\r\n* Remove patches from home.\r\n* If signs of infection in the form of redness, warmth, swelling, growing and throbbing pain, fever and red lines stretching from the wounds from the armpit or groin, seek medical advice.', 'Sores & blisters', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1098-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:32:52', '2012-01-12 12:32:52', '', 1098, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1098-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1453, 1, '2012-01-12 12:32:07', '2012-01-12 12:32:07', 'Exposure to sun can cause burns and heatstroke. The nearer the equator you are, the greater the risk. The sun is strongest at midday, and the effect is enhanced by water, snow and sand. Sunbeams may serve even in the shade, and can penetrate the thin, loosely woven or tight clothing.\r\n\r\nSmall children should not be exposed to direct sun, and should never be decidedly sunbathe. Use physical sunscreen, and wearing the smaller children nationwide, thin and loose clothing. Remember a hat.\r\n\r\nTravel advice - sunbathing:\r\n\r\n* Do not stay in direct sun for several hours straight.\r\n* Avoid the strong midday sun.\r\n* Apply sunscreen with a high SPF every 2-4 hours and after swimming.\r\n* As a rule of thumb, you should use at least a handful of sunscreen when you apply yourself. Otherwise, you risk using too little.\r\n* Protect especially the ears, nose, shoulders and lips.\r\n* Use sunglasses with UV protection and fits tightly to the face.\r\n* Protect your head with a hat, cap or similar.\r\n* Stay in sunshade.\r\n* Drink plenty of fluids.', 'Sun', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1095-revision-4', '', '', '2012-01-12 12:32:07', '2012-01-12 12:32:07', '', 1095, 'http://flufighters.org.uk/1095-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
